## The numbers first

```text
10M notifications/day
  = 10,000,000 / 86,400 seconds
  = ~116 notifications/second average
  = up to 500/sec during peak hours (morning, evening)

Channel split (assume):
  Email: 60% → 70 emails/sec avg, 300/sec peak
  Push:  30% → 35 push/sec avg, 150/sec peak
  SMS:    10% → 12 SMS/sec avg, 50/sec peak
```

---

## High-level architecture

```text
[Upstream services]
  Order Service → place order event
  Marketing     → campaign events
  Auth Service  → login alert events
        ↓
[Notification Ingestion API]    ← accepts events, deduplicates, publishes to Kafka
        ↓
[Kafka topic: notifications.raw]   ← single intake topic, high throughput
        ↓
[Notification Router Service]  ← reads raw, routes to channel topics
        ↓
  ┌─────────────────────────┐
  ↓            ↓            ↓
[email.send] [sms.send] [push.send]  ← channel-specific Kafka topics
  ↓            ↓            ↓
[Email Worker] [SMS Worker] [Push Worker]
  (SendGrid)   (Twilio)     (FCM/APNS)
  ↓            ↓            ↓
[Delivery Status → Redis + PostgreSQL]
  ↓
[DLQ: notifications.failed] ← failed after retries
```

---

## Step 1 — Ingestion API with idempotency

```java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/notifications")
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class NotificationIngestionController {

    private final RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;
    private final KafkaTemplate<String, NotificationEvent> kafka;

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<Void> ingest(
            @RequestBody NotificationRequest request,
            @RequestHeader("Idempotency-Key") String idempotencyKey) {

        // Deduplication via Redis (24-hour TTL)
        String dedupeKey = "notif:dedup:" + idempotencyKey;
        Boolean isNew = redis.opsForValue()
            .setIfAbsent(dedupeKey, "1", 24, TimeUnit.HOURS);

        if (Boolean.FALSE.equals(isNew)) {
            // Already received this exact notification request
            return ResponseEntity.ok().build(); // 200 OK, silently ignored
        }

        // Route to Kafka
        NotificationEvent event = NotificationEvent.builder()
            .id(UUID.randomUUID())
            .idempotencyKey(idempotencyKey)
            .userId(request.getUserId())
            .channels(request.getChannels())  // ["email", "push"]
            .templateId(request.getTemplateId())
            .payload(request.getPayload())
            .build();

        kafka.send("notifications.raw", request.getUserId(), event);

        return ResponseEntity.accepted().build(); // 202
    }
}
```

**Why idempotency key**: Upstream service might retry if our API returns 500. Without dedup, user gets 3 "Your order is confirmed" emails for 1 order.

---

## Step 2 — Router: fan-out to channel topics

```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class NotificationRouter {

    private final KafkaTemplate<String, NotificationEvent> kafka;

    @KafkaListener(topics = "notifications.raw",
                   groupId = "notification-router",
                   concurrency = "4")   // 4 consumer threads
    public void route(NotificationEvent event) {
        // Fan-out: one raw event → one message per channel
        for (String channel : event.getChannels()) {
            String topic = switch (channel) {
                case "email" -> "notifications.email";
                case "sms"   -> "notifications.sms";
                case "push"  -> "notifications.push";
                default -> throw new UnknownChannelException(channel);
            };

            kafka.send(topic, event.getUserId(), event);
            log.info("Routed notif {} to channel: {}", event.getId(), channel);
        }
    }
}
```

**Fan-out example**: User places order → 1 raw event → 2 channel events (email + push). Router sends to both `notifications.email` AND `notifications.push`.

---

## Step 3 — Email Worker with retry and DLQ

```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class EmailWorker {

    private final SendGridClient sendGrid;
    private final DeliveryStatusService statusService;

    @KafkaListener(topics = "notifications.email",
                   groupId = "email-workers",
                   concurrency = "8")  // 8 threads for email
    public void send(NotificationEvent event) {
        try {
            String html = renderTemplate(event.getTemplateId(), event.getPayload());
            SendResult result = sendGrid.send(
                event.getPayload().get("to"),
                event.getPayload().get("subject"),
                html
            );

            // Track successful delivery
            statusService.markDelivered(event.getId(), "email", result.getMessageId());
            log.info("Email sent for notification: {}", event.getId());

        } catch (Exception e) {
            log.error("Email send failed for notification: {}", event.getId(), e);
            statusService.markFailed(event.getId(), "email", e.getMessage());
            throw e;  // re-throw → triggers Kafka retry
        }
    }
}
```

**Retry + DLQ configuration:**

```java
@Configuration
public class KafkaConsumerConfig {

    @Bean
    public DefaultErrorHandler emailErrorHandler(
            KafkaTemplate<String, NotificationEvent> template) {

        // Dead letter topic for emails that fail after retries
        DeadLetterPublishingRecoverer recoverer =
            new DeadLetterPublishingRecoverer(template,
                (record, ex) -> new TopicPartition("notifications.failed", 0));

        // Retry 3 times with exponential backoff: 1s → 2s → 4s
        ExponentialBackOff backoff = new ExponentialBackOff(1000L, 2.0);
        backoff.setMaxAttempts(3);

        DefaultErrorHandler handler = new DefaultErrorHandler(recoverer, backoff);

        // Don't retry on bad data (template not found) — send to DLQ immediately
        handler.addNotRetryableExceptions(TemplateNotFoundException.class);

        return handler;
    }
}
```

**What happens when SendGrid is down:**
```text
10:30:01 ERROR EmailWorker - Email send failed for notification: abc-123
